al norms, and the very ability to conceive of another or oneself as marriageable, Marriage and Marriageability rethinks cross-border marriage not only as a form of gendered migration, but also as a set of practices that constructs marriageable partners and imaginable marriages. Yamaura shows that instead of desiring different others, these transnational marital relations are based on the tactical deployment of socially and historically created conceptions of proximity between Japan and northeast China. Far from seeking to escape local practices, participants in these marriages actively seek to avoid transgressing local norms. By doing so on a transnational scale, they paradoxically reaffirm and attempt to remain within the boundaries of local marital ideologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDating serviceszChinazManchuria. 0aDating serviceszChina. 0aDating serviceszJapan. 0aEthnologyzChinazManchuria. 0aEthnologyzChina. 0aEthnologyzJapan. 0aIntercountry marriagezChinazManchuria. 0aIntercountry marriagezChina. 0aIntercountry marriagezJapan. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aGender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aJapan, China, Migration, cross-border marrige, Gender studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175